00:27:53,672 --> 00:27:55,799
Careless and stupid...

243
00:27:55,940 --> 00:27:57,965
and now you're sorry, too.

244
00:27:58,109 --> 00:28:00,407
He said he...
He said he was alone.

245
00:28:00,512 --> 00:28:03,845
- I didn't know he had
any relatives. Honest.
- You made a mistake?

246
00:28:03,948 --> 00:28:05,745
- Is that what you're saying?
- Yeah. Yeah.

247
00:28:05,850 --> 00:28:08,683
Uh-huh. And I see you're anxious
to make up for it, aren't you?

248
00:28:08,787 --> 00:28:11,813
Yeah. Yeah, right.
Yes. Yes, sir.

249
00:28:11,956 --> 00:28:16,222
We've got another client
and he's about to select a new playmate.

250
00:28:20,432 --> 00:28:23,735
Next time send us
the one we ask for.

251
00:28:23,735 --> 00:28:27,728
I will, Mr. Fouchon,
I swear. L...

252
00:28:29,207 --> 00:28:32,335
I think
we understand each other.

253
00:28:32,477 --> 00:28:36,140
- Yes? No?
- Yes. Yeah.

254
00:28:36,281 --> 00:28:38,215
Randal.

255
00:28:38,316 --> 00:28:41,012
I come back here,

256
00:28:41,152 --> 00:28:43,052
I cut me a steak.

257
00:28:48,493 --> 00:28:50,393
You did your best.

258
00:28:50,495 --> 00:28:52,929
No, l...
I came too late.

259
00:28:53,064 --> 00:28:56,556
I mean, Jesus, he was living
out of a shopping cart.

260
00:28:56,701 --> 00:28:59,568
Goddamn it.

261
00:28:59,671 --> 00:29:02,640
Why didn't he just...
tell me?

262
00:29:02,774 --> 00:29:05,334
Why didn't he ask
for my help?

263
00:29:05,477 --> 00:29:09,277
I've been there myself
on the street.

264
00:29:09,380 --> 00:29:11,814
It's hard.

265
00:29:11,950 --> 00:29:13,850
It's hard to...

266
00:29:13,952 --> 00:29:15,920
put your hand out.

267
00:29:16,054 --> 00:29:18,852
I just kept thinking
if I could...

268
00:29:21,693 --> 00:29:24,594
just tell him
that I loved him.

269
00:29:26,531 --> 00:29:30,023
And because
he loved you so much,

270
00:29:30,168 --> 00:29:32,932
he didn't want to
pull you into it.

271
00:29:39,577 --> 00:29:41,477
- Our friend, Mr. Boudreaux.
- Mm-hmm.

272
00:29:42,947 --> 00:29:44,778
Silver Star.

273
00:29:44,883 --> 00:29:46,783
Marine Force Recon.

274
00:29:46,885 --> 00:29:49,683
He joined
the Merchant Service after he got out.

275
00:29:49,788 --> 00:29:51,915
His captain
was smuggling opium.

276
00:29:52,056 --> 00:29:55,719
When Boudreaux found out,
he threw the man overboard.

277
00:29:55,860 --> 00:29:58,294
He's been looking
for work ever since.

278
00:29:58,429 --> 00:30:01,921
He's obviously not someone
we should underestimate.

279
00:30:02,066 --> 00:30:05,263
He was raised
in the bayous by his uncle.

280
00:30:05,403 --> 00:30:07,598
I think Mr. Boudreaux...

281
00:30:07,739 --> 00:30:10,299
would make
a very interesting quarry.

282
00:30:11,943 --> 00:30:15,003
Maybe I should, uh,
pay him a visit.

283
00:30:15,146 --> 00:30:17,046
No, no, no, no, no.

284
00:30:17,148 --> 00:30:20,777
Send a couple of lads down there
to have a chat with him.

285
00:30:20,919 --> 00:30:22,819
Yeah.

286
00:31:09,701 --> 00:31:11,692
Yeah.

287
00:32:00,652 --> 00:32:02,620
Bingo.

288
00:32:35,787 --> 00:32:39,120
Some friendly advice, Boudreaux:
Get the fuck outta Dodge!

289
00:32:39,223 --> 00:32:42,249
Do it today! And tell
that bitch girlfriend of yours...

290
00:32:42,393 --> 00:32:45,260
to point her titties north
and step on the gas!

291
00:32:53,037 --> 00:32:55,301
It's always
nice to see you.

292
00:32:55,406 --> 00:32:57,772
You seem to have a real talent,
Mr. Boudreaux,

293
00:32:57,875 --> 00:32:59,843
for attracting violence.

294
00:32:59,944 --> 00:33:02,344
Does that make me
a bad person?

295
00:33:03,715 --> 00:33:05,615
Why did you arrest me for,

296
00:33:05,717 --> 00:33:08,345
getting beat up
without a license?

297
00:33:08,453 --> 00:33:12,321
Thank you for calling me.
Oh, my God, you look awful.

298
00:33:12,423 --> 00:33:14,789
Darling,
you hurt my feelings.

299
00:33:14,892 --> 00:33:17,326
What we have here is a charge sheet.

300
00:33:17,428 --> 00:33:20,920
Willfully crossing a police barrier;
that's considered Criminal Trespass.

301
00:33:21,032 --> 00:33:24,195
Yes, that officer was nice enough
to mention that to me.

302
00:33:24,302 --> 00:33:26,770
- What were you doing at the house?
- The dog tag...

303
00:33:26,871 --> 00:33:29,305
you find in that fire?

304
00:33:29,407 --> 00:33:31,307
They always come in twos.

305
00:33:31,409 --> 00:33:34,537
So I went back to that place
to look for the other one.

306
00:33:36,280 --> 00:33:39,511
Your daddy,
he didn't die in the fire.

307
00:33:41,119 --> 00:33:44,054
- He was murdered.
- There's no evidence of that.

308
00:33:44,155 --> 00:33:46,180
There is now.

309
00:33:48,292 --> 00:33:52,456
That hole in that tag was made
by something sharp and hard.

310
00:33:52,563 --> 00:33:55,191
And I'll bet my rent money
it was made...

311
00:33:55,299 --> 00:33:58,166
when Binder
was still wearing it.

312
00:33:58,269 --> 00:34:01,796
Why would somebody go through all
this trouble to kill a homeless man?

313
00:34:01,906 --> 00:34:05,842
- Do you believe us now?
- The wheels turn slow around here.

314
00:34:05,943 --> 00:34:08,503
- Real slow.
- But they do turn.

315
00:34:11,749 --> 00:34:14,240
I'll order a new autopsy.

316
00:34:14,352 --> 00:34:16,252
This'll help.

317
00:34:24,495 --> 00:34:27,896
- You should see a doctor.
- I hate them doctors.

318
00:35:01,199 --> 00:35:03,099
Yeah... Aah! Shit!

319
00:35:03,201 --> 00:35:05,101
Goddamn it.

320
00:35:06,270 --> 00:35:09,706
What? Not now.

321
00:35:19,016 --> 00:35:21,576
So... So, you in 'Nam?

322
00:35:21,686 --> 00:35:24,211
Yeah,
a long time ago.

323
00:35:24,322 --> 00:35:26,415
It seems to me a man with
your obvious experience...

324
00:35:26,524 --> 00:35:28,424
should be pullin' down
a lot more money.

325
00:35:31,662 --> 00:35:34,961
You're gonna pay me 100 bucks
to fill out a form?

326
00:35:35,066 --> 00:35:37,933
I'll pay you a lot more than that
if you got the experience.

327
00:35:42,373 --> 00:35:44,933
What kind of experience?

328
00:35:45,042 --> 00:35:47,135
Well, maybe you ain't interested.

329
00:35:47,245 --> 00:35:49,839
Uh, no.

330
00:35:49,947 --> 00:35:52,313
I'll fill out
the application.

331
00:35:52,416 --> 00:35:55,112
You got any family?
Anybody to worry about you?

332
00:35:55,219 --> 00:35:57,187
Friends?
Anything like that?

333
00:35:57,288 --> 00:35:59,688
I got nobody.

334
00:36:17,375 --> 00:36:21,004
You'll deposit
$500,000 in our account...

335
00:36:21,112 --> 00:36:23,012
in a bank
in the Cayman Islands.

336
00:36:23,114 --> 00:36:26,208
Do not refer to
our agreement by telex...

337
00:36:26,317 --> 00:36:28,217
or in conversations
on the phone.

338
00:36:30,321 --> 00:36:33,222
You'll be provided
with a guide, trackers...

339
00:36:33,324 --> 00:36:35,622
and the weapon
of your choice.

340
00:36:35,726 --> 00:36:38,092
Naturally, we will
dispose of the body...

341
00:36:38,196 --> 00:36:42,633
and provide you with
an out-of-town, airtight alibi.

342
00:36:42,733 --> 00:36:46,601
Don't worry, Mr. Zenan, all you
have to do is point and shoot.

343
00:36:54,946 --> 00:36:58,006
Mr. Zenan has made his selection.

344
00:36:58,115 --> 00:37:02,347
A black man named Roper.
Used to be in Special Forces.

345
00:37:02,453 --> 00:37:04,478
Excellent.

346
00:37:04,589 --> 00:37:07,023
I don't see any problem
with your choice.

347
00:37:07,124 --> 00:37:09,649
It has always been
the privilege of the few...

348
00:37:09,760 --> 00:37:11,660
to hunt the many.

349
00:37:11,762 --> 00:37:16,096
Soldiers, policemen,
fighter pilots.

350
00:37:16,200 --> 00:37:19,033
Men who kill for the government
do so with impunity.

351
00:37:19,136 --> 00:37:21,229
All we do is offer
the same opportunity...

352
00:37:21,339 --> 00:37:23,603
for private citizens
such as yourself.

353
00:37:23,708 --> 00:37:28,008
- These opponents, they're volunteers?
- More or less.

354
00:37:28,112 --> 00:37:30,876
The same government that has
made murder their sole preserve,

355
00:37:30,982 --> 00:37:32,882
they train our targets.

356
00:37:32,984 --> 00:37:36,215
We pride ourselves
on only hunting combat veterans,

357
00:37:36,320 --> 00:37:38,345
men who have
the necessary skills...

358
00:37:38,456 --> 00:37:42,085
- to make our hunts more interesting.
- What about the police?

359
00:37:42,193 --> 00:37:45,026
I'm sure that they would be interested
if they were to find out.

360
00:37:45,129 --> 00:37:47,563
Dr. Morton here
assists us...

361
00:37:47,665 --> 00:37:50,532
with the formality
of police autopsies.

362
00:37:50,635 --> 00:37:53,126
It's no accident
that we're in New Orleans.

363
00:37:53,237 --> 00:37:56,798
Last year we conducted hunts
in Rio de Janeiro at Carnival,

364
00:37:56,907 --> 00:37:59,205
Yugoslavia during
the late unpleasantness.

365
00:37:59,310 --> 00:38:01,369
Oh, yeah.

366
00:38:01,479 --> 00:38:05,643
You see, there's always some unhappy
little corner of the planet...

367
00:38:05,750 --> 00:38:08,344
where we can ply our trade.

368
00:38:08,452 --> 00:38:10,352
All right, Mr. Fouchon.

369
00:38:12,189 --> 00:38:15,647
- You have a client.
- Well,

370
00:38:15,760 --> 00:38:18,490
thank you for visiting,
Mr. Zenan.

371
00:38:18,596 --> 00:38:20,996
Dr. Morton will
show you to the car.

372
00:38:21,098 --> 00:38:23,794
My bank will arrange
the transfer of funds within the hour.

373
00:38:23,901 --> 00:38:26,131
- Excellent.
- When do we go out?

374
00:38:26,237 --> 00:38:29,832
We'll contact you when the
necessary arrangements have been made.

375
00:38:38,582 --> 00:38:41,779
Chance. What you doing here?

376
00:38:41,886 --> 00:38:45,151
- Secret mission.
- Mmmm.

377
00:38:45,256 --> 00:38:49,192
Rub me, baby.

378
00:39:06,444 --> 00:39:08,674
Oh, yeah, baby.

379
00:39:08,779 --> 00:39:11,441
Hello, Poe.

380
00:39:11,549 --> 00:39:14,484
What the fuck?

381
00:39:14,585 --> 00:39:17,452
- You miss me?
- Aw, Christ, not again.

382
00:39:17,555 --> 00:39:19,580
Looks like you're short
an ear,

383
00:39:19,690 --> 00:39:22,386
so you better listen
very carefully.

384
00:39:22,493 --> 00:39:27,123
- Now, are you paying attention?
- Uh-huh.

385
00:39:27,231 --> 00:39:29,290
Who sent those apes
after me?

386
00:39:29,400 --> 00:39:31,459
I don't know
what you're talking about.

387
00:39:33,671 --> 00:39:35,696
Two million people
in this city.

388
00:39:35,806 --> 00:39:39,401
- Who's gonna miss a fat
slob like you, Poe, huh?
- Van Cleaf!

389
00:39:39,510 --> 00:39:41,410
H-His name was Van Cleaf.

390
00:39:41,512 --> 00:39:43,503
Good boy.
Where is he?

391
00:39:43,614 --> 00:39:47,072
I don't know where he lives!
He ain't even American!

392
00:39:47,184 --> 00:39:50,017
Look, he'll... He'll kill me
if I don't do what he says!

393
00:39:50,121 --> 00:39:52,453
You gotta believe that!
Aaah!

394
00:39:52,556 --> 00:39:54,990
Tell your boyfriend
Van Cleaf...

395
00:39:55,092 --> 00:39:58,528
I'm gonna find out who
killed Douglas Binder.

396
00:39:58,629 --> 00:40:01,860
If you understand me,
just grunt.

397
00:40:03,968 --> 00:40:06,937
Again.

398
00:40:19,183 --> 00:40:23,085
Did you get my memo?

399
00:40:23,187 --> 00:40:26,020
Binder, Douglas C.

400
00:40:26,123 --> 00:40:29,024
I want you to take another look
at the post-mortem.

401
00:40:30,561 --> 00:40:34,361
That memo contains evidence...

402
00:40:34,465 --> 00:40:38,128
that might make
Binder's death a homicide.

403
00:40:38,235 --> 00:40:41,432
Now, you can act on it, Doctor,
or you can file it,

404
00:40:41,539 --> 00:40:45,236
but if I have to get a court order
for a formal inquest,

405
00:40:45,342 --> 00:40:47,776
I will.

406
00:41:02,092 --> 00:41:04,322
You should do something
about that cough.

407
00:41:04,428 --> 00:41:08,421
Don't you ever knock?

408
00:41:17,341 --> 00:41:21,505
We have a problem.
A big problem.

409
00:41:21,612 --> 00:41:24,240
They want me to redo
the autopsy on Binder.

410
00:41:27,885 --> 00:41:31,844
- Who is it that's asking?
- A detective named Mitchell.

411
00:41:31,956 --> 00:41:34,356
Binder's family's
breathing down her neck.

412
00:41:35,726 --> 00:41:38,786
- Can we buy her?
- No.

413
00:41:45,369 --> 00:41:48,202
I guess we've overstayed
our welcome.

414
00:41:51,909 --> 00:41:54,537
Tonight is our last hunt
in New Orleans.

415
00:42:01,552 --> 00:42:04,043
Open it.

416
00:42:35,719 --> 00:42:38,119
What a funny
little man, eh?

417
00:42:38,222 --> 00:42:41,089
A change of scenery's what we need.
Something less tropical.

418
00:42:42,860 --> 00:42:44,828
Rolling hills, castles.

419
00:42:46,897 --> 00:42:49,263
Eastern Europe.
We can work there for years.

420
00:43:27,037 --> 00:43:30,370
- Where's Poe?
- Mr. Poe couldn't make it.

421
00:43:30,474 --> 00:43:32,374
He's got an ear infection.

422
00:43:35,579 --> 00:43:38,412
Look, he, uh, he said
he'd have some work for me.

423
00:43:38,515 --> 00:43:41,382
That may still be
a possibility.

424
00:43:43,020 --> 00:43:46,217
We got a little game
we'd like you to play with us.

425
00:43:48,993 --> 00:43:51,086
This money belt...

426
00:43:51,195 --> 00:43:53,993
has $10,000 in it.

427
00:43:54,098 --> 00:43:57,090
It's all yours if you want it,
every penny.

428
00:43:58,202 --> 00:44:00,568
What do I have to do?

429
00:44:00,671 --> 00:44:03,606
The rules of the game
are very simple.

430
00:44:03,707 --> 00:44:07,336
All you have to do is get to the river.
Ten miles through the city.

431
00:44:07,444 --> 00:44:11,904
You and the money belt make it
to the river, you're $10,000 richer.

432
00:44:12,016 --> 00:44:13,916
Bullshit.

433
00:44:15,119 --> 00:44:17,383
Maybe you like being
the object of pity,

434
00:44:17,488 --> 00:44:20,582
begging for quarters,
sleeping in the rain,

435
00:44:20,691 --> 00:44:23,091
listening to a half an hour
of fire and brimstone...

436
00:44:23,193 --> 00:44:26,492
- for a bowl of soup.
- Man, fuck you.

437
00:44:26,597 --> 00:44:28,758
You could change everything
tonight.

438
00:44:28,866 --> 00:44:32,461
Think of what $10,000
could buy you.

439
00:44:32,569 --> 00:44:35,800
You could get new clothes,
clean yourself up,

440
00:44:35,906 --> 00:44:39,342
look men in the eyes when
you pass them on the street.

441
00:44:39,443 --> 00:44:42,435
This money could
make you a man again,

442
00:44:42,546 --> 00:44:45,640
instead of the shadow
of your former self.

443
00:44:51,422 --> 00:44:54,880
- I get to the river, I get the cash.
- Every nickel.

444
00:44:57,428 --> 00:45:02,058
- If I don't make it?
- Oh, you're a sports fan, Roper.

445
00:45:02,166 --> 00:45:04,634
Figure it out.

446
00:45:14,511 --> 00:45:17,912
You've got a five minute head start.
Don't waste it.

447
00:45:42,106 --> 00:45:45,098
This is New Orleans,
Mr. Zenan,

448
00:45:45,209 --> 00:45:47,109
not Beirut.

449
00:46:25,849 --> 00:46:27,749
After you, sir.

450
00:46:30,587 --> 00:46:33,181
- Mr. Zenan, take it off "safe."
- Oh.

451
00:47:34,551 --> 00:47:36,985
Finish him.

452
00:47:37,087 --> 00:47:40,955
I don't want him. H-He's wounded.

453
00:47:41,058 --> 00:47:43,492
- Finish him.
- I can't do that. I hit him.

454
00:47:43,594 --> 00:47:47,963
- I shot him. Let's go, okay?
- Listen, don't make me look bad
in front of my dogs.

455
00:47:48,065 --> 00:47:49,965
You know why you're here?

456
00:47:50,067 --> 00:47:52,194
You paid us a
half a million dollars...

457
00:47:52,336 --> 00:47:54,896
to find out
if you're alive or dead.

458
00:47:55,038 --> 00:47:57,768
Now finish him.

459
00:47:57,908 --> 00:48:00,274
Finish him!

460
00:48:00,377 --> 00:48:02,811
God, why didn't he
go fishing?

461
00:48:41,685 --> 00:48:44,415
Now you understand why we
insist on payment up front.

462
00:48:48,058 --> 00:48:49,958
Here.

463
00:48:51,395 --> 00:48:53,886
Set the dogs on him,
won't you, Pick?

464
00:48:54,031 --> 00:48:55,760
I don't wanna be out here
all night.

465
00:49:01,872 --> 00:49:05,239
Help me!
Please! Please!

466
00:49:12,482 --> 00:49:15,349
Help me!

467
00:49:15,452 --> 00:49:17,784
H... Please!
Help me! Help me!

468
00:49:17,888 --> 00:49:19,788
- Go on, get a job!
- Please!

469
00:49:19,890 --> 00:49:22,916
- Please!
- Watch it! Damn! Watch yourself!

470
00:49:23,060 --> 00:49:26,587
Help me. Help me!

471
00:49:26,730 --> 00:49:31,133
Help me! Please!

472
00:49:37,074 --> 00:49:39,065
Hey, look!
Come on, man!

473
00:49:39,209 --> 00:49:42,144
- Walk on by, now, man.
- Call the police here or somethin'!

474
00:49:42,279 --> 00:49:44,076
Help me!

475
00:49:46,116 --> 00:49:48,482
- Hey! Hey! Let me in! Come on, man!
- No, we're closed!

476
00:49:48,585 --> 00:49:50,553
Let me in!

477
00:49:50,687 --> 00:49:53,019
Hey, buddy!
Hey! Hey! Come on!

478
00:49:53,123 --> 00:49:55,887
- Brother, get out of here, man.
Come on, get out of here.
- Hey, come on, man!

479
00:49:55,993 --> 00:49:59,121
- Help me!
- Hey! I ain't got no change, man!

480
00:51:40,964 --> 00:51:43,797
He was passin' out flyers
for Randal Poe.

481
00:51:43,900 --> 00:51:46,494
Let's pay him a visit.

482
00:52:47,464 --> 00:52:50,331
Randal, Randal, Randal.

483
00:52:51,768 --> 00:52:55,169
You were gonna leave
without saying good-bye?

484
00:52:57,407 --> 00:52:59,932
My mama got sick in Biloxi.
L...

485
00:53:02,212 --> 00:53:04,373
I was gonna call you,
